          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Warning for China</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-3-2.jpg" alt="Warning for China" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4; filter: blur(5px);">During a visit to Beijing, German Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/germanys-baerbock-warns-china-over-russia-support/a-70934902" target="_blank">warned</a> that Russian President Vladimir Putin is pulling Asia into the Ukraine conflict. She expressed concerns about China potentially supplying drones or components to Russia and stated that such actions could damage the relationship between China and Germany. Baerbock criticized China and North Korea's <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/10/24/asia/russia-china-north-korea-iran-new-axis-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">support</a> for Russia, calling it a threat to European security.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4; filter: blur(5px);">Trade was also another key topic. Baerbock urged China to work on electric vehicle (EV) tariffs with the EU. While Germany opposes the <a href="https://www.euronews.com/business/2024/11/29/eu-and-china-advance-towards-alternative-solution-for-ev-tariffs#:~:text=The%20European%20Commission%20decided%20to,reductions%20on%20the%20proposed%20tariffs." target="_blank">EU’s tariffs</a> on Chinese EVs, fearing repercussions for German carmakers in the Chinese market, China argues the tariffs violate fair trade principles and has hinted at retaliatory measures.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
